<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Carrier Enterprise Battle Groups to Leave Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The United States is going
to reduce its forces in the Persian Gulf with the aircraft carrier
Enterprise battle group leaving the region at the week's end, the
Pentagon said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The forces left will be adequate to do what we need to do,"
Pentagon spokesman Lt. Col. Pat Sivigny said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that after the Enterprise leaves to patrol the
Mediterranean, another carrier, the Carl Vinson, will remain in
the Gulf region, along with more than two dozen other ships, 200
aircraft and 20,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
Another Pentagon spokesman Col. Rechard Bridges said
coalition air crews would continue to enforce the no-fly zones in
northern and southern Iraq despite recent exchanges of fire
between U.S. warplanes and Iraqi air defense batteries.
</P>
<P>
"None of this has affected our ability to enforce the no-fly
zones," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Operation Northern Watch also released a statement
declaring Western resolve to respond to any Iraqi challenges in
the no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
"Coalition air crews will continue to operate in a defensive
mode as they patrol the northern no-fly zone," the statement
said. "If threatened, they will act in self-defense to protect
U.S. and coalition forces."
</P>
<P>
Iraq remained defiant. "The battle against the aggression and
aggressors has not stopped. It will continue," Iraqi Deputy
Prime Minister Tariq Aziz said in remarks published on Thursday
in a front-page commentary in an Iraqi newspaper, called Al-Thawra.
</P>
<P>
Bridges said that, during Wednesday's exchange of fire, four
F-16 fighters and an EA-6B electronic warfare aircraft blasted an
Iraqi anti-aircraft site with two missiles and up to eight
laser-guided bombs after Iraq fired six to eight missiles at
British bombers in the southern no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
"It appears we hit the targets," Bridges said.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman David Leavy said the United States and
its allies would continue to carry out their mission and keep
Iraq contained and limit its ability to threaten its neighbors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
