<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of China Completes First Euro Transaction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of China said today
it successfully completed its first euro-related transaction,
involving 20 million U.S. dollars just one hour after the European
Union issued exchange rates for its 11 members this afternoon in
Brussels.
</P>
<P>
As the first financial institution in China dealing in euro
accounts and exchange, the Bank of China has prepared to offer
euro-related business services to Chinese and overseas
counterparts and clients via its global network, including
branches in Frankfurt, Paris, Milan and London.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of the euro against the yuan was set at
968.05 yuan for 100 euro for buying, and 970.95 yuan for 100 euro
for selling.  
</P>
</TEXT>
