<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke123154 -Pak to Re-invigorate Ties with Iran: Foreign Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Secretary Shamshad
Ahmed said Thursday the focus of his discussions in Tehran during
his upcoming visit would be "to re-invigorate an abiding
relationship" between Pakistan and Iran.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad is leaving for Tehran Friday on a two-day visit. He is
to deliver a special message of Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif to
Iranian President Muhammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
The Pak-Iran friendship and cooperation "remains a mutual
necessity," he was quoted by the Associated Press of Pakistan
(APP) as saying in an exclusive interview.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad said that during his stay in Tehran, he will hold two
rounds of talks with his Iranian counterpart on all the issues
concerning the Pak-Iran relations.
</P>
<P>
This sense of mutual need, strengthened by the "manifold
commonalties, rather than small irritants sowed by outside
forces," lay down the foundation of their close and mutually
beneficial relationship, he said.
</P>
<P>
Their relationship derives its strength from geo-strategic
compulsions and deep historical links between the two countries,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad said, he would seek "expansion of mutually beneficial
cooperation in all areas of common interest."
</P>
<P>
The visit to Tehran, he said, was in the context of follow-up
of the understanding reached between Prime Minister Sharif and
Iranian President Khatmi during their meeting in New York in
September this year.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders had agreed not only on the "need for
preservation of the abiding friendship between our two countries
but also for its expansion to make it commensurate with that
special relationship that we have shared between the two
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Pak-Iran relationship, based on trust and mutual
understanding, he said, "is serving the vital interests of the two
countries as well as the cause of regional stability."
</P>
<P>
He hoped that during his stay in Tehran, the two countries will
be able "to remove any misgivings or misunderstanding that may
have aroused because of factors which are extraneous to Pak-Iran
relations."
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Secretary said, Afghanistan is not the only canvas
of relations between Pakistan and Iran. If at all it is, "it is a
point of convergence rather than divergence."
</P>
<P>
"Afghanistan is our neighbor for whose legitimate interests
both Pakistan and Iran had struggled together for peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
A peaceful and stable Afghanistan, he said, is in the interests
of all countries in the region including Iran.
</P>
<P>
To a question, he said, "the allegations that Pakistan has been
supporting the Taliban is totally baseless. We only support the
Afghan people."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the unfortunate incident of the northern Afghan
town, Marzar-e- Sharif, in which eight Iranians were killed,
Shamshad said, Pakistan had taken up the matter with the Taliban
to ensure safety of Iranians there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
