<HEADLINE> Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao Urges Cleaning Up Taihu Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Wen
Jiabao recently urged a successfully battle against the
environmental pollution problems in the Taihu Lake Valley, setting
an example for the whole nation.
</P>
<P>
Wen stressed that the first stage in the fight against
pollution in the Taihu Lake Valley has been successful, but the
task ahead remains heavy and strict checks of compliance with
environmental law must be conducted to safeguard the achievements
already reached.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Council's requirements, all polluters in
the Taihu region must meet state standards for waste water
emissions by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The State Environmental Protection Administration (SEPA)
conducted a thorough check of some major polluters tonight,
together with officials from local governments.
</P>
<P>
It was just reported from Hangzhou, a major city in the region,
that more than 700 officials have randomly checked 17 enterprises
and all have met the state standards. Some entrepreneurs expressed
their surprise at being inspected as late as 11 p.m. on New Year's
Eve, and now sense the government's resolve to win this battle.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-seven percent of the major polluters have been found to
have met the state standards in 1998, according to Xie Zhenghua,
director of SEPA.
</P>
<P>
But there is still a long way ahead. Along with the Taihu Lake
Valley, China will launch anti-pollution projects in other rivers
and lakes in 1999, a key time for China to achieve its
environmental protection aims in this century, Xie added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
