<DOCNO> XIE19990101.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Another Town Falls to Rebels in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Another major town in Sierra
Leone, Lunsar, has fallen into the hands of the rebels fighting
against elected President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, reports reaching
here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A report by the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) quoted
Francis Okello, the United Nations representative to Sierra
Leone, as saying that the west African peacekeeping force,
ECOMOG, has withdrawn from the town, which is about 100
kilometers to the east of the capital Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Another report reaching here quoted post office workers in
contact with Lunsar as saying that the rebels moved into the town
Wednesday, after the withdrawal of ECOMOG troops.
</P>
<P>
Before the fall of Lunsar, the rebels have captured Makeni,
the northern regional capital that is about 100 kilometers to the
northeast of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Okello said the latest advance by the rebels means that the
whole of the northern half of the country is now under rebel
control in one form or another.
</P>
<P>
But a spokesman for the ECOMOG force has reportedly denied the
fall of Lunsar.
</P>
<P>
The rebels, comprising the Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
which took up arms in 1991 and loyalists of the May 1997 coup
that was kicked out of Freetown in March 1998, intensified their
attacks in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
In the face of renewed rebel threat, the United States and
Britain have evacuated their nationals while the United Nations
also withdrew part of its staff to neighboring Guinea.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, which provided the bulk of the ECOMOG troops, has
airlifted more than 7,000 reinforcement troops to Freetown in the
past few days.
</P>
<P>
Other west African countries, including Mali, Gambia and
Benin, have pledged troops but have been waiting for promised
international support to deploy them.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have threatened to attack Freetown on New Year's
Day, but ECOMOG said Freetown is now safe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
