<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Seeks U.N. Support for Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- As the fighting between
government and rebel troops intensified in Sierra Leone, Nigeria,
which plays a major role in sub-regional efforts to defend its
neighboring government, has appealed for urgent assistance from
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here Thursday said Nigeria's ambassador to
the U.N., Ibrahim Gambari, has met the five permanent members of
the Security Council to press for urgent actions by the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Gambari said the meeting Wednesday in New York was to get the
council to understand the urgent need to fulfill its
responsibility to support the peace efforts in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
He said he asked the permanent members, including China,
France, Russia, Britain and the United States, to tighten the
arms embargo on Liberia and the illegal flow of arms to the
rebels in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
He also appealed to the council to investigate countries
violating the embargo on arms supply to the rebels, namely
Liberia and the mercenary citizens of Ukraine who are fighting
alongside the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Gambari asked the council to prevail on the international
community to honor the pledges they made to support the Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) and its peacekeeping
force, ECOMOG, that has been supporting the government of
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian envoy asked the council to get U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan to be more pro-active in getting
U.N. members to support the needs of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Gambari explained that Nigeria is currently going through a
financial difficulty which has made the continuation of the
present level of its involvement impossible.
</P>
<P>
As Nigeria is expecting its first civilian government in 15
years in May 1999, it is impossible to expect the new government
to continue to maintain the current level of involvement, he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the envoy, the response of the five permanent
members to his request is positive.
</P>
<P>
"They said they will bring all these concern to the council
immediately and to convey all these urgent requests to their
respective countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a report by the British Broadcasting Corporation
(BBC) Thursday said the Gambia has begun an effort to mediate an
end to the fighting in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Gambian Foreign Minister Mohamed Lamin Sedat
Jobe as saying that the Gambia is trying to secure a ceasefire as
quickly as possible.
</P>
<P>
The minister gave no details but said he is confident of
success.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Sierra Leonean capital Freetown Thursday said the
rebels have captured another major town Lunsar, which is about
100 kilometers to the east of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
Following the fall of Lunsar and that of Makeni earlier, the
rebels now control the northern half of the country, U.N.
representative in Freetown, Francis Okello, was quoted as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
