<DOCNO> XIE19990101.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Community Urged to Solve Cyprus Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' President Glafcos
Clerides on Thursday called on the international community to act
more decisively and to fulfill its responsibilities in resolving
the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
In his New Year message, Clerides said that Cyprus' goal of
joining the European Union (EU) is beginning to be realised with
the opening of substantive talks in November.
</P>
<P>
"A more decisive and dynamic stand on the part of the
international community will give a new dimension to the
catalytic role our accession course to the EU may play on the
Cyprus problem," Clerides said.
</P>
<P>
He assured that it was the Cypriot government's consistent
strategy to encourage and help the international community in
effective involvement in the Cyprus problem so that a settlement
would be reached.
</P>
<P>
He said that the support from Greece remains vital for Cyprus'
EU accession effort.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot president highlighted the significance of the Joint
Defense Doctrine between Greece and Cyprus in the maintenance of
peace and stability of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The joint defense pact concluded in 1993 stipulates that Greece
will come to Cyprus' aide in case of a new Turkish offensive.
</P>
<P>
The solution of the Cyprus problem and Cyprus' accession to the
EU are the two major objectives of the Cypriot government,
Clerides reiterated.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Nicosia's struggle for EU membership was
made difficult due to the "intransigent stand" of the Turkish
Cypriot sides.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Cyprus is ready to give everything to safeguard
its freedom, human and national dignity in the face of provocation
or attack, "however strong the enemy might be."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
Efforts to settle the Cyprus issue reached a stalemate after
the Turkish Cypriot side demanded recognition of "the Turkish
Republic of Northern Cyprus", unilaterally declared in 1983 and
recognized only by Ankara. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
