<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Following are economic briefs
from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Sudan produced 6 million tonnes of cereals in
1998, said Minister of Agriculture and Forests Ali Nafie.
</P>
<P>
The remaining cereal stock from last year stands at 700,000
tonnes, reported the Alam Al Yom daily Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Most Sudanese cereal products are wheat and maize. During the
years 1996 and 1997, the average annual production of cereals
amounted to 5.3 million tonnes, whereas, average annual
consumption stood at 4.2 million tonnes.
</P>
<P>
In October, the Sudanese government lifted the ban on exports
of maize to help raise local prices which had declined due to
excessive supply.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture is the mainstay of the Sudanese economy. It
constitutes 95 percent of the country's exports, and between 40
to 50 percent of the gross domestic product, and provides
jobs to some 80 percent of the labor force.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Cotton products rank the second among Egypt's exports,
accounting for some 39 percent of the exports volume during the
period from 1994 to 1997, said a report by the Egyptian Ministry
of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The report, carried by the Alam Al Yom newspaper Thursday,
said that 79 percent of the cotton products go to western Europe
and the United States, and the rest goes to eastern Europe,
Africa, Asia and Arab states.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The Saudi Arabian Consulting Services firm has
called upon Saudi businessmen and investors to engage in the
production of palm oil.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, Saudi Arabia imported about 160,000 tonnes of palm oil.
This amount dropped to some 100,000 tonnes last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
