<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Fails to Meet Beef Export Quota </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe has failed to meet
its export quota for the third year running due to the Cold
Storage Company (CSC) debt burden, high interest rates and the
depleted head, the Cattle Producers Association (CPA) said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
CPA Chairman John Heynes said in the latest issue of the
Farmer magazine that it was expected that only 6,000 tons would
be achieved this year, far less than the required quota of 9,100
tons.
</P>
<P>
He noted that during 1996 and 1997, 6,600 tons and 6,560 tons
were exported respectively.
</P>
<P>
The marketing and debt problems faced by the CSC, he said,
were hindering the operations of the company, hence the failure
to perform up to expectations.
</P>
<P>
Due to low slaughter levels, Zimbabwe had failed to take
advantage of a duty free quota of 5,000 tons to South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Only a few abattoirs passed export standards approved by the
European Union, thereby limiting the export ability," he said.
</P>
