<HEADLINE> US, British Warplanes Resume Patrol over no-Fly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 31 (Xinhua) -- U.S. and British
warplanes resumed their patrol on Thursday over no-fly zones in
Iraq and returned safely after the mission, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
Pentagon spokesman Lt. Col. Pat Sivigny said Thursday's
flights were routine in both the northern and southern no-fly
zones, despite renewed Iraqi threats to challenge U.S. and
British planes monitoring the no-fly zones.
</P>
<P>
"No violations have been reported in either no-fly zone,"
Sivigny said.
</P>
<P>
Two clashes between U.S. and British planes and Iraqi air
defense batteries have occurred this week. One took place on
Monday in the northern no-fly zone when U.S. warplanes from
Incirlik base, Turkey, attacked an Iraqi anti-aircraft site
after it launched missiles at the jets. The other happened on
Wednesday when U.S. warplanes attacked Iraqi targets after
Baghdad fired missiles at British and U.S. aircraft flying the
southern no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and British planes suspended their patrolling
mission over the no-fly zones on Tuesday because of weather.
</P>
