<HEADLINE> Tanzania Waives Maize Imports Duty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa announced Thursday that the country has waived
maize import duty as a measure to solve the impending food
shortage.
</P>
<P>
In his New Year message to the nation, Mkapa said Tanzania's
Strategic Grain Reserve (SGR) has fallen to the lowest level
since it was set up in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The country is short of 400,000 to 450,000 tons of food, or 25
to 30 percent below requirement, due to lack of precipitation in
most parts of the country during short rains season starting
September, Mkapa said in a televised speech broadcast in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
Only Kigoma Region in the west and some parts of the Lake Zone
in the north have received some rainfalls in the season, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa also encouraged businessmen to transport food from
harvest regions to grain deficit areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a desperate move to alleviate food shortage, the president
ordered local brewers not to use food crops for production.
</P>
<P>
The president also asked people not to be choosy about food,
saying that cassava, plantain and yams should be consumed as
well.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa advised people to prepare their farms as soon as
possible and plant drought resistant crops such as cassava and
millets, adding that valleys and lower basins should be used for
crops cultivation.
</P>
<P>
People with cattle should be prepared to sell some to buy food
while those with few cash or domestic animals should be prepared
to work hard for food. 
</P>
</TEXT>
