<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Crimes Down in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has seen a
decline of crime rate from 395,079 cases in 1997 to 386,278 in
1998, or 2.23 percent, a statement from the Home Affairs Ministry
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It said that the crimes include 323,046 cases of criminal
offenses, 63,117 cases of traffic accidents and 115 cases of
train accidents, with the criminal offenses accounting for 83.63
percent of all the crimes.
</P>
<P>
In the criminal cases, mob justice, armed robbery,
superstitious belief and fighting led to 1,683 killing incidents,
leaving 1,731 people dead and 1,182 others arrested under
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
Other crimes which recorded an increase comparing with those
in 1997 are rape by 35.28 percent, defilement by 15.73 percent,
theft of government properties by 26 percent and drug trafficking
by 0.77 percent.
</P>
<P>
In transportation incidents, 1,214 people died and 8,934
injured in road accidents while 37 people died and 26 injured in
train accidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
