<HEADLINE> Mkapa Vows to Continue Fighting Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa said Thursday that the country will continue with
its anti-corruption campaign in the year 1999.
</P>
<P>
In his New Year message to the nation, Mkapa urged people to
report corrupt officers in their areas to him or to the Prime
Minister. He also called on people to refrain from bribing
officials as it encourages graft practice.
</P>
<P>
During 1998, he said, the government spared no efforts in
combating corruption. However, he admitted it was not an easy
task.
</P>
<P>
"No country in the world has ever eradicated corruption
completely," he said in a televised speech broadcast in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on security situation during the past year, the
president said tranquillity and peace prevailed in the country,
except for the bombing of U.S. embassy in Dar es Salaam and
banditry incidents caused by refugees in border regions.
</P>
<P>
To maintain social order, Mkapa said some 3,000 policemen were
recruited during the passing year, and their equipment have
improved.
</P>
<P>
On the achievements of medical care, he said districts have
been given more responsibilities in running the sector. In
addition, District and Hospital boards were formed in Dar es
Salaam, northwestern Kagera Region and in Igunga District in the
northern Tabora Region.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, he said, district and hospital boards will be
launched in 35 districts.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Ministry of Health has completed drawing the
Health Sector Reform Action Plan (1999-2002).
</P>
<P>
On the leakage of national Form Four examination papers, he
said, the incident has revealed the decay of the nation's morale
and irresponsibility of some people.
</P>
<P>
"Which nation are we trying to build when the would-be
doctors, engineers and academicians would attain their
qualifications by dubious means?" he queried. 
</P>
