<HEADLINE> Schroder: Europe will Master Globalization with Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The single currency euro, set for
its historic launching at midnight, will help Europe to master the
challenges of globalization, German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said
in an interview published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the business daily Handelsblatt, Schroeder said the period of
"nations going it alone in economic and financial policy" was now
over. With a common currency, cooperation in Europe must be
strengthened, he added.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder called the new single currency "Europe's key to the 21st
Century" and said that the euro actually had withstood its first tests
on international markets, while acceptance of the new currency among
Europeans was gaining.
</P>
<P>
"With the euro behind it, the European Union is well prepared for
the changes in the world economy," Schroder said.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder also said that in addition to the fiscal policy stability
package to assure the euro's stability, there must also come an
employment package.
</P>
<P>
"The people can't be sold politically on a stability package
without an employment package," he told Handelsblatt.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper also reported on a survey taken of bank economists
who predicted the 11 "Euroland" countries - Austria, Belgium, Finland,
France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Portugal,
and Spain - would see favorable starting conditions of only 1.5 per
cent inflation in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Most of the experts surveyed foresaw the euro rising by 10 percent
on the dollar next year, which would give the European Central Bank
room to lower its key interest rate to 2.75 percent, from the current
3.0 percent. Some experts even foresaw a rate cut down to 2.5 per
cent, Handelsblatt said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
