<HEADLINE> IMF Considers New Lending to Russia in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, January 1 (Xinhua) - The International Monetary Fund is
considering the possibility of lending to Russia under a new
Extended Facility Fund (EFF) program for 1999-2001, the Interfax
news agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In June 1998, the IMF Board of Directors decided to prolong
by one year the previous 9.2 billion U.S. dollars program
expiring in March 1999 because the fund was lagging behind the
initial disbursement schedule.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government, on its part, requested the IMF to
consider the possibility of launching the new extended financing
program.
</P>
<P>
Under the new program, Russia hopes to borrow 7--8 billion
U.S. dollars, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the IMF offered Russia 6.14 billion U.S. dollars,
1.34 billion of the sum in tranches of the EFF program and 4.8
billion in the framework of a stabilization loan approved by the
IMF Board of Directors on July 20.
</P>
<P>
This means total lending almost tripled from 1997 when the
IMF disbursed 2.1 billion U.S. dollars under the EFF program.
</P>
<P>
In the second half of 1998, the IMF planned to disburse 12.5
billion U.S. dollars, 1.3 billion of it agreed upon earlier in
the framework of EFF and 11.2 billion in additional stabilization
loans. However, given the crisis in August and the failure of the
Russian government to observe the terms of financial aid, the IMF
suspended disbursements.
</P>
<P>
Another IMF mission is expected in Moscow in mid-January. It
would decide about the possibility of disbursing the second 4.3
billion U.S. dollars tranche of the stabilization loan. The
Russian government attaches great hopes to the tranche which
Russia was to receive in September 1998 under the initial plan.
</P>
<P>
According to IMF reports, Russia owed a total of 19.5 billion
U.S. dollars to the Fund on September 1. In 1999 Russia is due to
pay the IMF 4.6 billion U.S. dollars on loans and interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
