<DOCNO> XIE19990101.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Needs Adjustment to Euro Introduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The introduction of the Euro on
January 1 may result in less foreign investment in Thailand if the
country fails to improve its financial, industrial and legal
systems to meet the internationally accepted standards.
</P>
<P>
"If the Euro is sufficiently stable and does help lower
interest rates and diminish production costs in Europe as
designed, more European and other foreign firms may transfer their
investments to Europe and that could cause trouble to
cash-strapped Thailand which badly needs foreign currencies to
right its ailing economy," the Thai News Agency on Friday quoted
Nimit Nanthapanthawat, chief of the Research Center of the Bangkok
Bank, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Thailand can also expect heated competition and there are
chances that the country will lose several European markets should
more European countries, which manufacture the same kind of
products as Thailand does, enter this single-currency zone, Nimit
said.
</P>
<P>
"With the advent of the Euro, Europe can become the economic
rival to the United States. It is expected that the single
currency will in the long run contribute to the annual economic
growth of at least 1 percent in Europe," he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the preparations in the financial and legal
systems, Thailand and other countries in Southeast Asia should be
more economically unified as to create a strong bargaining power
at international level, and a united effort is always more
effective than an isolated endeavor, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It quoted other economists as saying the Euro may result in the
declining of Thai exports due to the stronger baht. The U.S.
dollar is expected to decline after the introduction of the
European single currency, which means the baht will surge and then
unavoidably affect Thai exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
