<HEADLINE> N.Irish Leaders Call for Greater Progress in Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LONDON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's unionist and
republican leaders on Friday called for more progress towards a
permanent peace settlement in their respective 1999 New Year
messages.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland's First Minister David Trimble said peace in
the province must be secured in the next 12 months.
</P>
<P>
In his message, Trimble said more had been achieved in the
past year than most people would have believed possible, but
there was still much to be done.
</P>
<P>
"1999 must be the year in which peace is finally and
completely secured. In the referendum, the people voted for a
real peace," said Trimble, who is also the Ulster Unionist Party
leader.
</P>
<P>
"Whatever happens, 1998 was the year we crossed the
watershed. The mountains are behind us. There are still hills in
front, but I believe we can make our way through them," he added.
</P>
<P>
In a separate message, Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams said
if all parties honored their commitments to the agreement, they
could make major steps towards a lasting peace.
</P>
<P>
The major issues facing all sides were the establishment of
the Assembly executive, an all-Ireland ministerial council and
cross-border policy and implementations bodies, he said.
</P>
<P>
"If the political will exists, and if the parties to the
agreement honor their commitments, then progress will be made,"
said Adams. But he warned that progress could not be made until
Trimble "stopped looking over his shoulder at the past" and to
those in his party who were against change.
</P>
<P>
He urged the British and Irish governments to renew efforts
to move the process forward.
</P>
<P>
"For our part, Sinn Fein has repeatedly demonstrated our
commitment to the peace process," he said. "We are looking to a
new future, a new century, now only 12 months away."
</P>
<P>
The Assembly is due to meet later this month to ratify the
agreement on the structures of government for the province.
</P>
</TEXT>
