<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Pay $1.5 Billion Foreign Debt in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will spend 1.5 billion U.S.
Dollars for external debt service in 1999, the Head of State, General
Abdulsalami Abubakar said Friday in a national broadcast on the 1999 budget.
</P>
<P>
The sum is 50 million Dollars less than in the case of previous years.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar explained that this is due to resource constraints in
1999, mainly as a result of the slump oil price in the international
market, as Nigeria depends on oil export for more than 90 percent of
its export income and 80 percent of the budgeted income.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that even the two billion Dollars set aside for external
debt services in previous budgets has been below the requirement of Nigeria'
s creditors, and has resulted in the accumulation of substantial arrears.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, he said, efforts will be intensified to open up
negotiations with the Paris Club, the Bretton Woods Institutions and
other creditors to seek debt reduction and debt relief.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that Nigeria has already started discussion with the
above-said creditors toward evolving a program aimed at eventually
attaining debt relief for the country.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar also announced the lifting of the 1994 embargo placed on
external borrowing "in view of the projected deficit in the 1999 budget"
and the need for government to broaden the source of funding.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the borrowed money will be mainly spent on
export-based projects, including those in the oil and gas sectors.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's foreign debt now stands at between 28 billion to 34 billion
Dollars, according to the estimate of different sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
