<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Implements Revised Land Use Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- China today began imposing the
world's strictest land-use regulations to protect arable land
through the implementation of the revised Land Use Law in an
effort to ensure sustainable economic growth and social progress.
</P>
<P>
The new law requires that each province, autonomous region and
municipality guarantee that the amount of arable land under their
jurisdiction does not decrease, and that land quality is improved
at the same time.
</P>
<P>
Farmland under special protection should account for more than
80 percent of the total in each administrative region, according
to the law.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China will impose tighter reins on approving land use
for construction. The new law empowers only the central and
provincial governments with the right of approval, and raises
compensation for land acquisition.
</P>
<P>
To protect arable land, the new Land Use Law requires
governments at each level to take measures to improve the soil and
to prevent desertification, soil salinization and land erosion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
