chosen as British Person of the Millennium by listeners of BBC
Radio 4's news and current affairs program Today, the BBC
reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The playwright beat Sir Winston Churchill into second place
by a narrow margin with print pioneer William Caxton a little way
behind in third.
</P>
<P>
The result of the contest was kept a close secret until
announced on the New Year's Day edition of Today.
</P>
<P>
Over the Christmas period, listeners were asked to choose the
most outstanding figure of the last 1,000 years. Nominations were
reduced to a short-list of six. The other three on the short-list
were naturalist Charles Darwin, Physicist Isaac Newton and 17th
century civil war leader Oliver Cromwell.
</P>
<P>
More than 45,000 people voted by telephone for the eventual
winner. 
