<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Official Exchange Rate of Nigeria's Currency Abolished </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nigerian Head of State General Abdulsalami Abubakar announced this in
his 1999 budget broadcast to the nation Friday morning, saying that the
abolition of the official exchange rate would remove the long-standing
opportunity for personal gain at the expense of the public interest.
</P>
<P>
The application of the dual exchange rate did not allow for proper
evaluation of viable economic projects funded at official rate, he said,
adding that the practice had encouraged unprofitable projects in the
country.
</P>
<P>
"Public expenditure is transacted at the autonomous rate, revenue is
monetized at official rate, giving rise to a mismatch between revenue and
expenditure," Abubakar stressed.
</P>
<P>
In the broadcast speech, he said that the focus of the monetary policy
in 1999 would remain the maintenance of price stability as well as the
promotion of stability of the exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
The issue of the dual exchange rate introduced four years ago has been a
subject of tense debate in the most populous African country among experts
who have argued for or against the merger of the dual exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
Those who wanted the exchange rate merged argued that the retention of
the dual exchange rate was an incentive to corruption as well as creating
serious accounting problems in the country.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar also announced that the Nigerian government had granted
the Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) an autonomy in the formulation and
implementation of monetary policies.
</P>
<P>
According to him, this development was "in recognition of the critical
role which an independent central bank can play in the maintenance of price
stability and sound economic management."
</P>
<P>
An independent central bank will serve the best interest of the national
economy of Nigeria, said Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
The large scale fraud by the former Head of State Sani Abacha and his
aides was blamed on the lack of autonomy of the CBN by financial experts in
the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
