<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Air Pollution Still High in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Air pollution indexes for some
major cities in north China remained high over the past week,
indicating that serious air pollution has not been eased,
according to the weekly report issued by the China Environment
Monitoring Center today.
</P>
<P>
Experts attribute the polluted air in the cities to unfavorable
weather conditions in the early part of the week, and low wind
speeds were unable to disperse the unclean air.
</P>
<P>
The pollution indexes for Lanzhou, Hohhot, Xining and Jinan
were reported at over 300, with air quality ranked V, the highest
and most serious category of pollution, during December 25-31,
1998.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen cities including Beijing, Shanghai and Chongqing
reported indexes over 200, with an air quality of type IV during
the period.
</P>
<P>
Dalian, Chengdu, Guilin, Shenzhen and ten other cities enjoyed
good air quality of type II, and Shantou, Haikou and Xiamen
reported excellent air quality.  
</P>
</TEXT>
