<P>
The Egyptian leader criticized the Iraqi government as there
was a war of words going on between the two countries, both
trading accusations and name-calling in their media.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi papers, known to be controlled by the government, have
reportedly blamed Arab leaders, including Mubarak, for failing to
help Iraq have the U.N. sanctions lifted while Egypt's official
media accused Saddam himself of bringing about the disasters in
Iraq and causing the rift in Arab ranks by sending troops into
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqis have been reeling under eight years of crippling
sanctions imposed by the Untied Nations Security Council after its
1990 invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
In his interview with Al Ahram, Mubarak dismissed the call made
by Iraqi officials for not to draw a line between the ordinary
Iraqis and their ruling system.
</P>
<P>
"This is unacceptable talk at a time when the very same Iraqi
officials incite the Arab peoples to turn their backs against
their rulers," he told the paper.
</P>
<P>
"Has the Iraqi regime managed to patch up things with its Arab
brothers? Has this regime given up its ambitions and showed good
manners on having different views from others?" asked Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
"We are not supposed to replace this regime in undertaking its
responsibilities towards its people. The Iraqi regime has to take
the decisions beneficial to its people's interests, not the ones
that tamper with and squander these interests," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
