<HEADLINE> New Year Brings New Hopes for Hong Kong: Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong entered the year
1999 with hopes and dreams for a better future, which requires
continued and pains-taking efforts of both the government and
people, local newspapers said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of thousands of Hong Kong residents took to the streets
and counted down to the New Year Thursday night although the year
1998 had been struck by economic downturn, resulting in negative
economic growth and a higher jobless rate.
</P>
<P>
A commentary of Ta Kung Pao said the reason for the unhappiness
of Hong Kong people in 1998 was mainly from "external factors" and
the problems left over by history.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong returned to China on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
While the government of the Special Administrative Region (SAR)
made great efforts to overcome the difficulties, the Central
government has given "biggest possible support" to the SAR, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The festivities of the New Year's eve showed that Hong Kong
people cherish great hopes and confidence that the difficulties
will be overcome and economic recovery will soon start in the new
year, it said.
</P>
<P>
In a commentary, Wen Wei Po said Hong Kong has a relatively
favorable environment compared with other crisis-hit economies in
Asia since it is backed by China's mainland areas which enjoy a
sound economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The commentary called on the people of Hong Kong to "face the
reality" and work together to handle the existing problems so as
to further improve Hong Kong's strength in competition.
</P>
<P>
It appealed to employers and employees to adopt an attitude of
mutual understanding and coordination so as to narrow their
differences. It also hoped that politicians should "act with
caution" and not do anything to affect Hong Kong's stability or
dampen the enthusiasm of investors.
</P>
<P>
A commentary of Ming Pao Daily News described the year 1999 as
one of profit when people should strive for innovations and
reformation that will pave the way for future development.
</P>
<P>
The commentary said 1997 was a year of transition that
primarily requires stability and that 1998 was a year of
(economic) storm in which handling crisis is top priority.
</P>
<P>
It said Hong Kong people should take the advantage of "Hong
Kong people ruling Hong Kong" and meet the challenges of the
times.
</P>
<P>
A Sing Tao Daily commentary said Hong Kong can step into a new
century with a sound structure as long as it sticks to the current
path.
</P>
<P>
The commentary said Hong Kong has come to the dawn of economic
recovery. It said an overall growth of the world economy, although
such growth might be limited, will be helpful to the economic
recovery of Hong Kong. 
</P>
