on Iranian President Khatami to deliver a letter from Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad told the reporters before his departure that
developments in Afghanistan would not affect the friendly ties
between Pakistan and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan issue is one of the important topics for the two
countries during his Tehran tour, said Shamshad, adding that some
ugly incidents in war-torn Afghanistan will not harm relations
between Pakistan and Iran.
</P>
<P>
He dispelled the impression that Pakistan has any competition
with Iran in Afghanistan, saying that Afghanistan is important for
the relationship between two countries. Any incident in
Afghanistan will have no impact on the friendly Pak-Iran ties, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad also said relations between Pakistan and Iran are
based on cooperation to resolve the long-running Afghan problem.
"The ties have never been based on rivalry in Afghanistan as we
are not competitors," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked if there is a possibility of the revival of the Pak-Iran
joint peace mission for the solution of the Afghan crisis, the
Foreign Secretary said Pakistan has been in close cooperation with
Iran in all aspects. He said his visit to Iran is in line with the
continued consultations between the two countries. 
