<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1998: Year of Mixed Economic Blessings: Nigerian Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to Abubakar, Nigeria witnessed in 1998 some measure
of macro-economic stability and consolidation of the economic gains
attained in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar said that significant progress has also been made in
implementing economic reforms, including the removal of restrictions on
competition as well as private sector participation in various sectors of
the economy.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the economy suffered some setbacks which
adversely affected the implementation of the 1998 budget and the
realization of the set targets.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's crude oil production, which accounts for more than 90 percent
of its foreign currency income and 80 percent of budgetary revenue, has
suffered blows.
</P>
<P>
In its 1998 budget, the Nigerian government predicted an oil price of 17
U.S. Dollars per barrel, but due to the decline of oil price in the
international market, the commodity was sold at an average price of 12
Dollars per barrel.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to save the oil price, the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries (OPEC) slashed the quota of member countries, including
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The tension between oil companies and oil-producing communities in
southern Nigeria led to the closure of many oil wells and flow stations in
1998, which also reduced Nigeria's oil production and export.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Abubakar said, the budgeted 1998 revenue of 216.336 billion
Naira (one Dollar equals about 85 Naira) could not be realized.
</P>
<P>
By the end of October 1998, the country's actual receipts from
crude oil reached only 134.44 billion Naira, he said.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar concluded that the story in 1998 proved again Nigeria's
economic weakness, namely, the over reliance on oil revenue.
</P>
<P>
"A major development goal for the country, therefore, is to
diversify the production, foreign exchange and revenue base of the economy,"
he said, adding that the 1999 budget will provide the basis for achieving
this goal.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Abubakar disclosed that by the end of November 1998,
Nigeria's foreign reserve stood at 7.6 billion Dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
