<HEADLINE> Nigeria Aims  to Attain 3 Percent Growth in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria isl aimed to achieve a minimum
growth rate of three percent in 1999, Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar said Friday in a national broadcast on the 1999 budget.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian leader announced that in view of the slump in the global
oil market, the 1999 budget is based on the oil price of nine U.S.
Dollars per barrel, compared with 17 dollars per barrel in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Based on an exchange rate of 86 Naira to one Dollar, the budget
predicts a revenue of 453.7 billion Naira from the oil and gas sector,
while revenue from non-oil sector is estimated at 214 billion Naira.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar announced a total spending of 88 billion Naira on capital
projects, including those in agriculture, health, education, road, water
supply and rural electrification.
</P>
<P>
He also announced a spending of 1.5 billion Naira on poverty
alleviation and rural development, including one billion Naira for
the Family Economic Advancement Project and 500 million Naira for soft
loans and support services for rural and small-scale industries.
</P>
<P>
Despite a 54 percent fall in the expected total revenue, the budgeted
spending on salary increased from 56 billion Naira in 1998 to 100 billion
i9n 1999, due to increased salaries and allowances for civil servants.
</P>
<P>
The budget expects a total of 50 billion Naira in revenues from the
Value Added Tax (VAT). And according to the new distribution formula,
about 15 percent will go to the federal government, while the state and
local governments will get 50 and 35 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to the budget, the federal government will have a fiscal
deficit of 34.1 billion Naira in 1999, representing 1.05 percent of
projected gross domestic product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The budget provides 39 billion Naira for settlement of domestic
debt.  
</P>
</TEXT>
