<HEADLINE> Zambian Farmers Call for Eye-for-Eye Trade Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia National Farmers' Union (ZNFU)
has called on the government to impose non-tariff barriers on all
horticultural produce from neighboring South Africa and Zimbabwe to enable
Zambian farmers to compete fairly.
</P>
<P>
ZNFU President Ajay Vashee said the situation pertaining to the flooding
of horticultural products from the two countries in most shopping outlets
has not changed in spite of the presentations the union has made to the
authorities, according to Friday's Times of Zambia newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted the union leader as saying that unless the
trend is reversed, the Zambian farmers, especially the small-scale
horticulturist will be wiped out.
</P>
<P>
"Because of the non-tariff barriers that South Africa and Zimbabwe have
put in place, including some very tough administrative measures, the
Zambian farmers cannot sell even a single cabbage in Johannesburg or Harare
vegetable shop," Vashee complained.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Zimbabwean authorities has introduced a rule where any
Zambian farmer wishing to export to that country has to apply for
authorization from Harare.
</P>
<P>
If successful, such an authority is valid for only 24 hours after
which it can not be used to export anything, said Vashee.
</P>
<P>
"Imagine, that means one has to drive or fly to Harare to get the
authority and rush back to Zambia and export the goods within the time
frame, something practically very difficult," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that while Zambian farmers are finding it difficult to export
to the south, the Zambian market is free for the produce from South Africa
and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Concern has been raised in various fora about the amount of the two
countries' vegetables on the Zambian market, a development which has
wrecked the market for the Zambian farmers, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Some supermarkets insist on getting their supplies from the south
because Zambian farmers allegedly cannot meet the demands of consistence in
the supply and quality of fresh farm produce.
</P>
<P>
Vashee dismissed the excuse as unacceptable and baseless, arguing that
none of the farmers have been given contracts and failed to deliver.
</P>
</TEXT>
