<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Exports Hit by Asian Economic Crisis: UN Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, January 1 (Xinhua) - The ongoing Asian economic crisis
has slowed down the exports of many African countries and reduced the
overall growth rate in Africa by about one percent in 1998, according to a
United Nations report.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. report titled as Africa Recovery said that African countries
have been hit by the Asisn crisis directly and indirectly mainly through
lower
commodity prices in the international market, shrinking export markets as
well as reduced investment and other financial flows.
</P>
<P>
Local media Friday quoted the report as saying that the cotton exports
of Tanzania, the Sudan and Togo have dropped by 2.7 percent, 4.8 percent
and 2.3 percent respectively while Zambia's copper exports dropped by 25.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Oil exports of Algeria has dropped by 12.4 percent, Angola by 24.8
percent, Cameroon by 16.2 percent, Egypt by 5.9 percent and Nigeria by 24.3
pRercent.
</P>
<P>
Equatorial Guinea and Gabon wood exports declined by 9.9 and 4.6 percent
respectively while Ghana's aluminum exports declined by 4.1 percent, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, an economic giant in Africa, has also been hit by the
mounting global economic crisis and its exports to Asia have dropped to
some extent.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the impact of the Asian crisis on Africa is
now being felt both directly and indirectly because there has been a
greater reluctance of foreign investors to invest in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The decline of commodity prices will also affect growth and
investment, even slowing progress in poverty reduction", the report said,
estimating that Angola and Nigeria have lost a quarter of their anticipated
total export earnings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
