<HEADLINE> Museveni Optimistic About Uganda's Economy in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Museveni said this in his New Year message addressed to the nation on
radio and television Thursday night, a press release from the President's
Office said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The president said that Uganda's economy has continued to perform well
despite some setbacks resulting from the effects of the adverse El Nino
weather phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
He expressed confidence that the economy would reach a gross domestic
product (GDP) growth of seven percent in this financial year, up from 5.5
percent recorded in the previous one.
</P>
<P>
Some economic indicators were cited to show the healthy
development of the economy which include a 19 percent growth in private
investment, an annual headline inflation rate of minus 5.1 percent and an
underlying inflation of 3.1 percent (excluding food prices).
</P>
<P>
Museveni said that tax revenues are more or less on track in the sphere
of income tax and called on the revenue authorities to zero in on tax
erasion.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the importance of increasing the country's revenue
performance relative to GDP which at 11.3 percent, though much better than
the four percent in 1986, is still much lower than many
countries in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The president also promised to take more effective measures to eradicate
poverty, improve infrastructures and enhance the standards of social
service.  
</P>
