<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 09:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Punish Beirut for Guerrilla Attacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Israel's security cabinet has
decided to hold the Lebanese government responsible for any
rocket attacks on northern Israel launched by Hezbollah guerillas,
virtually rejecting a unilateral withdrawal from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting late Thursday night, the inner cabinet adopted an
Israeli army proposal that it will respond to any Katyusha rocket
attack on Israel by hitting a target in Lebanon, Israel Radio
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after the meeting, the security cabinet
said Israel "holds Beirut directly responsible" for what happens
in south Lebanon, demanding the Lebanese government stem guerilla
activities there and prevent rocket attacks on northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
Observers said by adopting this proposal, the Israeli
government has virtually ruled out a unilateral withdrawal from
the self-styled security zone in south Lebanon it carved out more
than 13 years ago.
</P>
<P>
As more soldiers lost their lives in the 15-kilometer-deep
buffer zone in the last few weeks, debates have heated up among
Israelis over the fate of their military presence there.
</P>
<P>
Many Israelis demanding a unilateral withdrawal argued that the
security zone, set up by Israel in 1985 to prevent cross-border
attacks by Hezbollah guerillas, has failed to provide security for
northern Israel but become a source of conflicts instead.
</P>
<P>
This view was driven home when Hezbollah guerrillas fired a
barrage of Katyusha rockets at northern Israel last week,
wounding 13 people, to retaliate the killing of a Lebanese woman
and six of her children in an Israeli bombing raid one day before.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli government has conditioned a withdrawal on a
security arrangement with Beirut, saying a unilateral pullout
would expose northern Israel to Hezbollah fires and endanger the
future of Israel's local militia allies, the South Lebanon Army
(SLA).
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and its main ally, Syria, have rejected Israel's
proposal, insisting that Israel should withdraw from south
Lebanon unconditionally.
</P>
<P>
At Thursday's meeting, the cabinet said it would make efforts
to protect the SLA as well as Israeli civilians in the north.
</P>
<P>
It also adopted a position held by Foreign Minister Ariel
Sharon, Internal Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani and other
ministers that Israel will not link its negotiations on the
Lebanese track with the Syrian track.
</P>
<P>
Syria has insisted a linkage between Israel's withdrawal from
south Lebanon with a solution to its dispute with Israel over the
Golan Heights, which was seized by Israel in the 1967 Middle East
war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
