<DOCNO> XIE19990101.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup:NZ Sharemarket to Get Brighter after Tough year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand sharemarket
is expected to become bullish after experiencing one of its most
difficult years in 1998.
</P>
<P>
It was punctuated by extreme volatility and record lows in
1998. The year saw the key NZSE40 Capital index falling to 1,668
points, about 1,000 points lower than a year ago, hitting a new
five-year low.
</P>
<P>
This means the combined value of the 40 leading stocks fell to
37 billion NZ dollars from 60 billion NZ dollars. Almost for the
whole year the NZSE40 Capital index fluctuated below the mark of
2,000 points.
</P>
<P>
On the bright side, the volume of the New Zealand stocks rose
about 60 percent and the number of trading increased 20 percent
compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
But, the general situation for the New Zealand sharemarket was
quite bad last year. Its bearish state was attributed mainly to
the slump of the economic activity in the country, which started
when the Asian crisis began to bite in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, the three cuts in interest rates by the Federal
Reserve, New Zealand's central bank, in October resulted in the
sharemarket trading up quite strongly.
</P>
<P>
At present, retail deposit rates in New Zealand banks have
plunged to their lowest level in nearly three decades. New
Zealanders have 43 billion NZ dollars (23 billion U.S. dollars)
deposited in banks.
</P>
<P>
Historically, low interest rates should serve as a panacea for
the sharemarket, especially in the first half of this year.
Investors who have had their earnings from bank deposits reduced
are likely to turn to equities offering better returns.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the country's GDP grew by 0.7 percent in the third
quarter of last year after a six-month contraction. The fourth
quarter is also expected to have a positive growth.
</P>
<P>
In the third quarter of last year, New Zealand exports were up
3.6 percent. There are evident signs of improvements in the wood
and paper products, petroleum and chemicals, and metal products
industries. Exports of these products as well as of meat and dairy
products have been rising in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
There is a general feeling that the worst is over and New
Zealand is emerging from economic recession or even has shrugged
off the recessionary blues. The majority of New Zealanders expect
this year will be better than last year and their country will see
a fairly broad-based recovery in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
A latest survey shows business confidence in New Zealand is now
at a four-year peak and up across all sectors of the economy. The
growing confidence in the economy was apparent last month in the
strong rally in the stock exchange. On the last day of 1998, the
NZSE40 Capital index exceeded the mark of 2,000 points and reached
2,084 points.
</P>
<P>
The recovery of the New Zealand sharemarket is dependent on
there being no big correction in global sharemarkets, interest
rates remaining at current levels and the country's economic
activity growing and company earnings improving.
</P>
<P>
In view of the current situation in the country, most local
sharebrokers predict that it will be possible for the NZSE40
Capital index to reach more than 2,300 points this year. More
optimistic economists are now expecting the NZSE40 index to climb
to as high as 2,600 points at the end of this year, levels last
seen immediately before the Asian crisis struck. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990101.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nairobi Stock Mart Ends 1998 on High Note </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NAIROBI, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Brokers in Kenya predicted that the
Nairobi
Stock Exchange (NSE) will continue to improve in the new year as it ended
1998
with a gain scoring its 19th win in 20 sessions in a day of desultory
trade Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The NSE 20-share index Thursday gained 8.42 points or 0.29 percent to
close at 2,953.64, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Brokers expressed the optimism that the index's recent rally would
continue
into the new year as investors continued to move away from the money
markets and into equities, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The 20-share index has gained over 15 percent since December 2 but 1998
is still likely to be remembered as one of the worst years for the Kenyan
bourse in 1990s, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
In July last year, the index slumped to a four-and-a-half year low with
prohibitive interest rates leaving equities unable to compete with high
yielding treasury bills.
</P>
<P>
Economic instability , characterized by a deep recession in manufacturing
industry and a crisis in the financial sector with leading banks reporting
large portfolios of non-performing loans, sent many foreign and
institutional investors scurrying for cover.
</P>
<P>
But with the average yield on Kenya's benchmark 91-day treasury bills
dropping to 11.068 percent at last week's auction from 27 percent in April,
the stock market has rebounded.
</P>
<P>
Commercial banks have responded by lowering the base lending to around 17
percent for the leading banks.
</P>
<P>
The lower interest rates have been praised by manufacturers and the local
business community.
</P>
<P>
Barclays Bank of Kenya was the biggest mover jumping four Shillings to
close at 130 on 9,287 shares.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said Barclays, the biggest international bank in Kenya, has
weathered the storm hitting the financial sector better than most of its
competitors and is widely considered as a growth stock.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Kenya posted an opening Shilling mean indicative rate
of 61.9056 against the U.S. Dollar from Wednesday's 62.15 Shillings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
