<HEADLINE> Japan Welcomes Launch of Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Japan has welcomed Friday's
launch of Europe's single currency euro and hopes to further
strengthen its ties with the 11 countries in the European
economic and monetary union.
</P>
<P>
"Today marks the birth of a new currency, the euro, which I
very much welcome ....We intend to further strengthen our
relationship with the euro-area countries in the fields of
economy as well as the international monetary system," Japanese
Finance Minister Kiichi Niyazawa said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the euro "is a great step forward toward a
closer economic and monetary union, which has been made possible
by the European countries' continued efforts in the past 30 or so
years," Niyazawa said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the new European currency will lead to greater
integration of the 11 nations' economies, further expand regional
trade and investment, and increase labor mobility, which will
result in higher economic growth in Europe.
</P>
<P>
The euro will also "play a significant role" in the internat
ional monetary system, given the large economic area it
represents, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Japan acknowledges the importance of the
internationalization of the yen, Niyazawa said Tokyo will
continue to make every effort in various fields to further
promote international use of the Japanese currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
