<HEADLINE> Bell Ringing Ushers in New Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The clock tickled down to the
end of 1998. In resounding bell tolls and thunderous cheers, China
stepped into the new year of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Sounding bells to welcome new year is an old Chinese
tradition. In the Dazhong Temple in the capital city of Beijing,
more than 1,000 visitors gathered at a new year eve party, which
ended in sonorous bell tolls of the "Yongle Bell", the largest one
in China with a weight of 46 tons.
</P>
<P>
"Bells are sounded only by emperors in the past, nowadays
commonplace people can also ring the bell to get rid of worries
and bad fortunes in the new year," said an American professor, who
has come to China to spend the new year holidays with 30 of his
American college students.
</P>
<P>
Visitors and residents in Hangzhou, a scenic city and capital
of eastern Zhejiang Province greeted the new year in tolls of the
"Nanping Bell" of the Jingci Temple, which was named after the
"Nanping Mountain" where the temple is located.
</P>
<P>
7:36, morning, sun is rising above horizon, so is the
five-star red flag at the Tian'anmen Square. More than 30,000
people of all ethnic groups gathered in the square to see the red
flag hoisted on the first day of 1999. The whole ceremony is
broadcast live by the China Central Television Station. 
</P>
</TEXT>
