<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Vows to Lift Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi welcomed the New Year by reiterating his resolve to put
Japan's sagging economy back on a recovery path.
</P>
<P>
"I hope to make this year a year in which we overcome
difficulties and work toward the future in a bold manner by
viewing (the crisis) as a chance," Obuchi said at a New Year
press conference.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi said his government will do its utmost to achieve the
target of 0.5 percent economic growth in fiscal 1999, which
starts from April 1.
</P>
<P>
"I am certain the government's policies and the private
sector's serious efforts will produce results and that the nation
will achieve clear positive growth in the next fiscal year," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi also said his cabinet will strive to give the nation a
sense of security in five areas -- economic recovery, employment,
the environment, social security and child rearing.
</P>
<P>
To stimulate the economy, the Japanese government has drawn up
an expansionary 81.86 trillion yen (about 705.7 billion U.S. doll
ars) state budget.
</P>
<P>
The immediate task for his government is to get a quick Diet
(parliament) approval of the budget bill, Obuchi said.
</P>
<P>
Toward that end, Obuchi said, his ruling Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP) intends to form a stable government in cooperation
with the Liberal Party (LP).
</P>
<P>
"I would like to see a firm and stable relationship between
the two parties, Therefore, I would like to seek the LP's
participation in the new cabinet," he said. 
</P>
