<HEADLINE> Philippines to Deploy "Mobile Teachers" in Remote Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
deploy "mobile teachers" in remote areas this year to equip young
indigenous folk and dwellers with the rudiments of reading,
writing and arithmetic.
</P>
<P>
In a report released here Friday, Undersecretary of Education
Victor Andres Manhit said that his department will offer "Mobile
Tutoring" services to people in remote islands, upland dwellings,
indigenous communities and even rebel-infested areas.
</P>
<P>
The department is recruiting 300 mobile teachers under the
"Mobile Literacy Project" to render teaching services, 40 hours
weekly, in such far-away places as Palawan and the Cordillera
Administrative Region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Manhit said beneficiaries of this non-formal education program
will be out-of-school youths, aged 15 and above.
</P>
<P>
Mobile teachers with handy instructional aids will visit remote
areas to teach people the "basics " of reading, writing and
computation as well as livelihood lessons, he added. 
