<HEADLINE> Chinese, U.S. Presidents Vow to Boost Bilateral Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
and his U.S. counterpart Bill Clinton Friday expressed the hope
to boost relations between the two countries on the occasion of
the 20th anniversary of the establishment of diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
In his congratulatory message, President Jiang extended, on
behalf of the Chinese government and people and in his own name,
cordial greetings and warm congratulations to President Clinton
as well as the government and people of the United States.
</P>
<P>
 "the normalization of China-U.S. relations was a milestone
in the history of our bilateral relations and also a major event
in the history of contemporary international relations. The
course of development of China-U.S. friendly and
mutually-beneficial cooperation over the past two decades gives
expression to the common aspirations of the two peoples. It
contributes to peace, stability and prosperity in the
Asia-Pacific region and the world at large, and accords with the
trends and requirement of the times," Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he has "seen with pleasure the significant
progress scored in China-U.S. relations in recent years.
</P>
<P>
" The two presidents "have had a successful exchange of
visits, together decided that our two sides would be committed to
the establishment of China-U.S. constructive strategic
partnership and reached identity of views on enhanced bilateral
cooperation in wide-ranging fields," the Chinese president said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the two countries have had good cooperation
on some major international issues. At present, the bilateral
relations are faced with new opportunities of development, said
Jiang.
</P>
<P>
He said that "the principles enshrined in the three Sino-U.S.
Joint Communiques are the basis for these relations" and facts
have proved that strict observance of these principles "will
ensure sound and stable progress of China-U.S. relations."
</P>
<P>
Jiang expressed the hope that the two countries would "work
together to move China-U.S. relations forward in the spirit of
mutual respect, seeking common ground while shelving differences,
broadening identity of views and promoting cooperation, and along
with other countries in the world, help bring a peaceful, stable
and prosperous world into the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
In his message to Jiang, Clinton said he was pleased to convey
the warmest wishes of the American people to the people of China,
the congratulations on the achievements of the Chinese people
over the past two decades, and the sincere commitment of the U.S.
government to increasingly cooperative and mutually beneficial
relations in the decades to come.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "As we mark the 20th anniversary of the
establishment of diplomatic relations between the U.S. and China,
we can take pride in the fruitful efforts you and I -- and our
predecessors -- have made to deepen and strengthen U.S.-China
relations."
</P>
<P>
He said, "the expansion of cooperation between the two nations
has increased mutual understanding and established the basis for
stronger future relations."
</P>
<P>
He said he is "personally committed to building a constructive
strategic partnership with China that will benefit the two
peoples and promote a stable and prosperous Asia-Pacific region."
</P>
<P>
He believed the exchange of visits by President Jiang and
himself in 1997 and 1998 furthered their ability to work together
to meet global and regional challenges critical to both countries.
</P>
<P>
Today, as the two sides celebrate their achievements over the
past 20 years, they should reflect on ways to strengthen their
ties for future generations, and they must work together to meet
the common challenges of the 21st century while frankly
addressing differences, Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the belief that the two sides will be able to
build the kind of partnership that will serve the interests and
hopes of the American and Chinese peoples. 
</P>
</TEXT>
