<HEADLINE> 1 Killed, 310 injured in Firecracker explosions in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- One person was killed and 310
were injured in firecracker explosions and gunfires in the past
two days in the Philippines, where many people greeted the new
year with firecrackers and firing of guns, the Philippine News
Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Partial reports received by the Philippine National Police
(PNP) as of noon Friday showed 14 people were hit by stray
bullets, causing one death, and 310 cases of firecracker
explosions, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
However, the Department of Health said the number of victims
could rise as soon as all reports from all regions come in.
</P>
<P>
Of the 14 victims of stray bullets, the agency said, 10 came
from Mindanao and four from Metro Manila.
</P>
<P>
Police arrested a Manila policeman and a soldier for firing
their guns to celebrate the new year, it said.
</P>
<P>
Based on the partial reports, firecracker explosions and firing
of guns decreased by 58 percent compared to 1997, the health
department said.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time that the country experienced a less
explosive New Year's Eve celebration. In the past, Filipinos
usually greeted the new year with unabated explosion of
firecrackers all over the country, particularly in Metro Manila.
Aggravating the situation was the indiscriminate firing of guns by
soldiers, policemen and civilian gun owners.
</P>
<P>
Weeks before the Christmas holiday, the government and
non-government organizations (NGO) launched a massive campaign
nationwide asking gunholders to refrain from firing their firearms
to celebrate the new year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
