<HEADLINE> 134 State-Owned Cinemas Privatized in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of 134 state-owned
cinemas have been privatized in Myanmar in different forms since
the country opened its door for private entrepreneurs to run the
cinemas.
</P>
<P>
Of the 134 cinemas owned by the Myanmar Motion Picture
Enterprise (MMPE), 22 were sold to local private entrepreneurs, 21
leased on a long-term basis under the BOT (Built, Operate,
Transfer) system and 91 leased on a yearly basis, the New Light of
Myanmar newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Plans are underway to lease 30 others now being run by the
MMPE, it said.
</P>
<P>
Cinema business in Myanmar is reportedly going down due to a
lower number of Myanmar films produced and high cost of foreign
films.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has, since January 1995, been implementing a
privatization plan for its state economic enterprises (SEE), aimed
at transforming them into effective business organizations.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the scheme covers 51 SEEs including
processing and manufacturing factories, livestock breeding farms
and cinemas, and is being implemented in various forms --
auctioning and leasing out the enterprises or establishing joint
ventures with local and foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
These enterprises include those nationalized during the time of
the Revolutionary Council government in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
In the privatization process, the government is striving to
ensure that in transferring to the private business people, local
Myanmar citizens take precedence over foreigners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
