<DOCNO> XIE19990101.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: 1999: Critical Stage for Asia's Adjustments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- With the beginning of the year
1999, Asia's economic adjustments have entered a most critical
stage, as the outcome of such adjustments in the next 12 months
would decide the fate of the region's economy in the years ahead,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Since a regional financial crisis began 18 months ago, Asian
countries, and those in Southeast Asia in particular, have
undertaken a series of adjustments in various economic sectors.
</P>
<P>
The initial outcome of the adjustments has contributed to a
rebound in regional currencies, stocks and foreign investments in
the past three months.
</P>
<P>
However, most of the adjustment measures taken by Asian
countries so far were aimed at containing the crisis, rather than
achieving a recovery, the analysts said. A full economic recovery
needs further and more effective adjustments.
</P>
<P>
In a recent report, the Asian Development Bank said the
region's outlook for 1999 depends on the fate of current reform
initiatives. Many economists also place their hopes for an
economic turnaround in Asia on further reforms.
</P>
<P>
In all economic sectors, repairing the region's banking system
is the most urgent and difficult task, as abnormal banking
operations are directly affecting a recovery process, economists
said.
</P>
<P>
During the last 18 months, banking bailouts were progressing at
a very slow pace despite closures and take-overs of some
debt-ridden financial institutions by governments in the region.
Non-performing loans are increasing instead of falling in many
Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
In Japan, non-performing loans of the nation's 17 biggest banks
totaled at 426 billion U.S. dollars as of the end of last March,
according to a report by the Financial Supervisory Agency, a
Japanese financial watch dog, in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
Japanese officials estimated that non-performing loans for the
whole Japanese banking sector have reached 700 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
As a major creditor of other Asian nations, Japan could hardly
provide new loans for Asia's recovery before it finishes cleaning
of its own house.
</P>
<P>
In the countries worst affected by the crisis -- Thailand,
Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines and South Korea, no funds
have been allocated to eliminate bad debts owed by banks. The
non-performing loan ratio of these countries is almost certain to
increase this year from the current 10 percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the non-performing loans, the five countries
owed about 175 billion dollars in short-term debt to international
banks as of mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
Although the Japanese government has pledged a 30 billion
dollar aid package to Asian countries for banking reforms, the
amount is far from enough.
</P>
<P>
The cost of recapitalizing Asia's beleaguered banks, excluding
those in Japan, could be as high as 64 billion dollars, said
global securities firm Merrill Lynch in a recent report.
</P>
<P>
To speed up the banks' resuscitation, experts suggested the
greater use of nationalization. By taking over banks, governments
would remove share-holders who are reluctant to write down the
value of their stakes, they said.
</P>
<P>
Being sole or majority owners, they said, governments would be
better placed to negotiate the debt-forgiveness and restructuring
deals with foreign creditors and local borrowers. And after
cleaning up the banks, governments can sell them back to the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
As an "engine" of the Asian economy, the region's export sector
also needs further adjustments. In the past year, Asian countries
have done virtually little in adjusting the export sector, which
is dominated by
production of electronics, textile and garments.
</P>
<P>
Partly because of weak demands in the regional and world
markets and partly because of a shortage of working capital and
falling prices,
exports in Asia fell remarkably for the third consecutive year in
1998. And accordingly, Asia's economic growth slowed down from 7.5
percent in
1996 to 6.1 percent in 1997, and to 1.8 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Governments also must look for a solution to over-capacity,
which has crushed prices, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
This problem is worst in electronics, which accounts for up to
50
percent of exports in the crisis-hit countries. Western markets
are
unlikely to keep soaking up Asian products even at lower prices.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Asian countries should make adjustments in the
export
sector by diversifying their products to solve the problem of
over-
supply.
</P>
<P>
The outlook for an export recovery would remain bleak until the

adjustment in the export structure is completed, experts said.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, some Asian countries must find new remedies for the
economy
as old prescriptions by the International Monetary Fund have
failed to save their economies in the past 18 months.
</P>
<P>
After the crisis broke out, the crisis-hit countries
implemented the
IMF's austerity programs by raising interest rates, lowering
growth targets and cutting budget deficits.
</P>
<P>
But under the austerity programs, all these countries fell into
a serious economic recession in 1998. During the latter part of
last year, even the IMF had to persuade these countries to
increase budget deficits to stimulate their economic development.
</P>
<P>
With the change of prescriptions, these countries must make
re-adjustments in their development strategy to achieve a quick
recovery, experts said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990101.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang: China's Ties with Western Countries Improved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- China's relationship with the
Western developed nations has been improved and developed in the
past year, Chinese President Jiang Zemin said here today.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, also General Secretary of China's Communist Party
Central Committee, made the remarks here this morning at a new
year reception sponsored by the National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, he said, Chinese and U.S. presidents exchanged visits
and both sides made efforts to help build a constructive,
strategic partnership.
</P>
<P>
The Sino-Russian strategic partnership is developing in a
smooth way, Jiang said, adding China and Europe have decided to
develop a comprehensive partnership.
</P>
<P>
He stated that China and Japan have decided to set up a
friendly cooperative partnership for peace and development, and
stressed that China has always placed importance on using the
history as a mirror to open up the future.
</P>
<P>
Jiang noted that in the past year, China has taken an active
part in activities of international organizations, including the
UN and the APEC, and played an important role on handling major
international issues.
</P>
<P>
China has also contributed to easing the Asian financial crisis
by offering necessary assistance to nations seriously affected by
the crisis and by not devaluing its currency RMB, thus improving
its international prestige and status, he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking highly of the diplomatic work which has scored
significant results, Jiang said China's good-neighborly ties with
neighboring nations have been furthered, while its unity and
cooperation with developing nations have also been continuously
consolidated.
</P>
<P>
All these have served to create a favorable international
environment for China's reform and opening-up, he said.
</P>
<P>
China will always stick to its independent foreign policy of
peace and promote the friendly cooperation with various countries,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people are ready to join other people in the world
to safeguard the world peace, promote common development, oppose
the hegemonism and power politics and make due efforts to help
stabilize the regional and world economic and financial situation,
and set up a fair and reasonable international new order. 
</P>
