<HEADLINE> Exchange Rate Set Between Bulgarian Currency, Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The exchange rate will go into effect as of January 4, 1999,
announced the People's Bank of Bulgaria, adding that exchange
rates with currencies of relevant European Union (EU) member
states have also been established.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate between the lev and the euro was worked out
on the basis of the new linking exchange rate system between the
lev and the German mark, the Bulgarian Telegraph Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Under the new system, one German mark is equivalent to 1,000
Bulgarian lev. The Bulgarian government has announced that the
lev's face value will be changed as of July 1, 1999, so that one
lev is equal to one German mark.
</P>
<P>
These moves are believed to be the steps needed to speed up
Bulgaria's financial integration into the European economy.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the start of the new European currency, Bulga
rian Prime Minister Ivan Kostov said he hoped that it would help
Bulgaria be adopted by the European Monetary Union and the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Bulgarians hoped the huge volume of the
single European financial market, surpassing six trillion euro,
will provide a broader and more convenient source of investment.
</P>
<P>
Of the total amount of foreign investment Bulgaria attracted
in 1998, the investment from EU member countries accounted for 76
percent, including 20 percent from Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
