<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Has Lowest Road Toll in 34 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The road toll in New Zealand
in 1998 was the lowest in 34 years with 503 people killed.
</P>
<P>
The New Zealand Press Association (NZPA) Friday quoted Land
Transport Safety Authority spokesman Dave Jones as saying while
the overall drop was pleasing, many deaths were avoidable.
</P>
<P>
Half of the people killed in 1998 were due to speeding,
drinking and driving, and people not wearing seat-belts, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the number of drivers killed last
year fell 11 percent to 225, the lowest since 1984, and the
number of passengers killed dropped from 166 in 1997 to 138, the
lowest since 1964.
</P>
<P>
The lower national toll in 1998 was attributed to a combination
of public response to publicity campaigns for drink driving and
better speed management on highways.
</P>
<P>
The national road toll for the Christmas and New Year holidays
from December 24 to Friday morning was 14, four less than at the
same time of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand saw the highest road toll in 1973 with 843 people
killed and the lowest road toll in 1964 when 428 people died.
</P>
</TEXT>
