<DOCNO> XIE19990101.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: 1998 Witnesses High Growth, Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Privatization, as a process of developing new technologies
and modern management systems instead of financial sell-off, is
a basic component of reactivating Mozambique's national economy.
</P>
<P>
By early June last year, 900 small- and medium-sized firms and
85 large ones of the 1,254 state-owned enterprises, had been
privatized. The rest will also have been done so by the end of
June this year.
</P>
<P>
The private sector has been playing a leading role in the
national economy. and more privatizations and leasing out port
and rail infrastructure to private management will come soon.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Transportation and Communications Paulo Muxanga
told Parliament last November that Mozambique will privatize all
the ports and railways company of the country at all costs but
would be very careful regarding the treatment of the workers.

Political Stability
</P>
<P>
Local government elections were successfully held in 33 cities
and towns across the country in June last year.
</P>
<P>
Although 15 opposition parties led by the largest -- the
Mozambican National Resistance Movement (RENAMO) -- boycotted the
elections, they all expressed their willingness, after the
results were made known, to cooperate with the newly-elected
local governments.
</P>
<P>
What's more, police across the country have taken effective
measures to fight various crimes. In capital Maputo alone,
police mopped up more than 110 gangs in the first nine months
last year.
</P>
<P>
The number of major and vile crimes has been declining in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Analysts hold that political stability and better security
have contributed to the good performance of the Mozambican
economy.

Debt Relief
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank
meeting in Washington last April took the final decision that
1.4 billion U.S. Dollars of Mozambique's debt would be written
off.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique is deemed eligible for the Highly Indebted Poor
Countries debt relief, with a waiting period of 15 months instead
of the usual 18 months.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1.4-billion-Dollar relief, 916 million Dollars have
been granted by bilateral creditors (mostly members of the Paris
Club which is the liaison body of the main creditor nations), and
526 million Dollars by multilateral agencies, mainly the World
Bank and the IMF.

More Investment
</P>
<P>
The Paris Club has so far provided 570 million Dollars in aid
to the Mozambicans while this southern African country had
attracted 360 million Dollars of foreign investment in the upper
half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
There are six foreign-funded projects under negotiations each
worth at least 50 million Dollars. Two big projects were started
in mid-1998. One is the 900-million-Dollar superhighway linking
Maputo with South Africa. Another is the 1.2-billion-Dollar
Mozal Project of the Mozambique Aluminum plant.
</P>
<P>
The plant is the most immediate development arising from the
Maputo Corridor project, the biggest industrial development now
taking place in Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
It involves the British company Billiton, Mitsubishi of Japan,
and the Commonwealth Development Corporation of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mozal will produce 250,000 tons of aluminum a year for export
using bauxite from Australia. After construction it will provide
400 permanent jobs and a number of local spin-offs.
</P>
<P>
However, the remarkable economic growth is still part of the
recovery in Mozambique, one of the world's poorest countries, and
long years of warfare and neglect have left about 80 percent of
its population in absolute poverty. This poses great challenges
to the Mozambican government in the future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
