<HEADLINE> Thai PM Determined to Call Early Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai has reaffirmed that he would call early general elections
after the passage of key organic laws required by the
constitution.
</P>
<P>
Chuan stressed in a new year speech made public on Friday that
he would keep his promise to quit before his four-year term ends.
</P>
<P>
He said his government's priorities were to tackle economic
problems and prepare the nation for a new general election.
</P>
<P>
"I believe all (the laws) will be completed in the next
parliamentary session," he said, referring to the next ordinary
sitting between June and October.
</P>
<P>
The constitution requires that key organic laws be passed in
two years after its promulgation, or by October 1999. Eighty
percent of these laws have reached parliament or are being
deliberated.
</P>
<P>
Coalition partners have called upon Chuan to complete his term
which ends in 2000 despite the rejection from the opposition.
</P>
<P>
The call came as the opposition was stepping up efforts to
launch a no-confidence motion against the coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Chuan has said the mission of his term was temporary and if the
economy picked up before 2000, he would dissolve the House of
Representatives and call a general election.
</P>
<P>
But key coalition figures have urged Chuan to change his mind,
saying his stay in office would serve the nation's interests.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said in the new year speech that he intended to lay a
firm economic foundation for the country but would not use this as
an excuse to buy time or to take advantage of other parties.
</P>
<P>
He said all parties were at the moment equally prepared for a
general election, and the question as to who was better would be
answered by looking at their lists of candidates.
</P>
<P>
But he did not say exactly when a new election would be called.
</P>
</TEXT>
