<HEADLINE> Chirac Sends Condolences to Widow of Prominent Chinese Writer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
sent a message expressing his condolences on the death of
prominent Chinese Writer Qian Zhongshu, praising his outstanding
contributions to the cultural exchanges between France and China.
</P>
<P>
In the message addressed to Qian's widow, Yang Jiang, Chirac
described Qian as "the embodiment of the finest features of the
Chinese nation: intelligence, elegance, Kindness, openness and
modesty.
</P>
<P>
"I pay my respects to this great man, who, in the history of
cultures, will remain a source of inspiration for future
generations, thanks to his boundless creativity, his vigilant
thinking and his sense of universality," the French president
said in the message, a copy of which was faxed to Xinhua by the
French embassy in China on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Qian died in Beijing on December 19 at the age of 88.
</P>
<P>
A graduate of Qinghua University of China and Britain's Oxford
University, Yang was known for his efforts to interweave Western
and Eastern cultures. He also studied at Sorbonne University in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
His most famous novel, "The Besieged City," depicts the ideas,
hopes and aspirations of Chinese intellectuals. He was also
respected for his collections of literary critiques.
</P>
<P>
In his condolence message, Chirac also said that "France
realizes how much she owns to this paramount scholar of the 20th
century. Since the days he was studying at the Sorbonne
University in Paris in the 1930s, Mr. Qian Zhongshu has
consistently honored French culture and shared his passion for
our writers and philosophers.
</P>
<P>
"His brilliance was such that he appealed to all his readers.
As you know, French translations of his works -- short stories,
his famous novel "The Besieged City" and his critical essays --
have been acclaimed as masterpieces by a very large audience in
my country," Chirac said in the message, which he signed on
December 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
