<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: 1998 Witnesses High Growth, Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Different from a large number of
other African countries which are haunted by either political
chaos or economic recession, Mozambique has been enjoying high
economic growth and low inflation in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Mozambique experienced the highest growth in southern
Africa, with its gross domestic product (GDP) reaching 2.2
billion U.S. Dollars for 1998, up by 11.2 percent over the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
From January to November last year, its inflation rate had
been 2.5 percent on average and the annual inflation is estimated
at two percent, the lowest in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
From January to September, Mozambique's exports topped 184
million Dollars, up by 1.5 percent over the similar period of
1997 while its import was 781 million Dollars, 66 million Dollars
down as against the 1997's.
</P>
<P>
Since the war ended in 1992, Mozambique's economy has
recovered quite rapidly.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, agriculture and animal husbandry grew by 4.9 percent,
industry and fishery by 11.3 percent respectively, mining by 28.7
percent, building materials by 43. 9 percent, construction by
eight percent and transport by 6.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Generally, the exchange rate of the Mozambican currency
Metical to the U.S. Dollar is stable.  Currently, one Dollar
equals to 12,323 Metical and the exchange rate at the black
market is only two percent higher than the official one.
</P>
<P>
Favorable weather, structural adjustment, political stability
and improved security, debt relief and incoming investment are
attributed to the good performance of the Mozambican economy,
analysts here said.

Favorable Weather
</P>
<P>
Mozambique had a bumper harvest last year and farming remains
the basis of the Mozambican economy. The grain output amounted to
1.69 million tons, up by 10 percent as against the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Production of the staple maize is expected at 1.124 million
tons, up by eight percent over 1997.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the favorable weather in most parts of the country,
only less than 700,000 hectares of farmland were affected by
drought or floods in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Planting acreage has been expanded to 3.72 million hectares,
increasing by 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
pricing of various farm products except cotton has been
liberalized by the government as an incentive to the farmers.
</P>
<P>
Good performance in agriculture has played an important role
in stablizing prices, keeping inflation low, reducing imports and
promoting the development of processing.

Tax Reform
</P>
<P>
The contribution of financial revenues to Mozambique's GDP
increased to 19.9 percent in 1998 from 19 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The government has reorganized the tax authorities, trained
tax collectors and computerized the process of tax collection as
well as lowered tax rates.
</P>
<P>
As a result, revenues collection increased remarkably
since the government expanded the areas for tax collection and
curbed tax evasion, and also improved the government's capacity
to fund essential services.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, although the running spending increased by 0.6
percent, its share in the GDP had dropped from 1994's 22.5
percent down to 18.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the growth of monetary supply has been contained
within 2.6 percent and the bank loaning rate to the government
also kept low since the government does not use bank loans to
fund its budget spending.
</P>
</TEXT>
