<HEADLINE> Foreign Exchange Reserves Rise in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's foreign currency
reserves rose significantly to 1.92 billion U.S. dollars as of
December 31, 1998, up 6.67 percent from 10 days earlier, said
Bangladesh Bank, the country's central bank.
</P>
<P>
The country's foreign exchange reserves soared up to the
highest level of 3.07 billion dollars on June 30, 1995, but
dropped to 2.03 billion dollars on June 30, 1996 and 1.71 billion
dollars on June 30, 1997, according to a bank press release
reaching here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The reserves fell to the lowest point of 1.6 billion dollars in
August 1998, but rebounded and rose to 1.8 billion dollars on
December 21, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The release did not say what had contributed to the rising
reserves, but earlier press reports said the increase in the
foreign exchange reserves was attributed to the inflow of aid in
cash and kind from the country's donors for emergency relief and
post-flood rehabilitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
