<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, IAEA Sign Additional Nuclear Protocol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- China has decided to keep the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) informed of its
cooperation with non-nuclear-weapon countries as well as its
imports and exports of nuclear materials.
</P>
<P>
Under an additional protocol to a strengthened safeguards and
supervision treaty signed by the two sides on Thursday, China
also promised the IAEA to verify any information about China's
nuclear issues presented by non-nuclear-weapon nations to the
IAEA.
</P>
<P>
China's permanent representative to the IAEA, Ambassador Zhang
Yishan and IAEA Director-General Mohammed el-Baradei signed the
additional protocol.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador pointed out that China signed the protocol for
the purpose of improving the efficiency and proficiency of the
IAEA with an aim to contributing to the efforts of achieving
nuclear non-proliferation in the world.
</P>
<P>
As one of the developing nations that own a small number of
nuclear weapons and a signatory nation to the Non-Proliferation
of Nuclear Weapons Treaty, China has shown its seriousness and
responsibility in fulfilling its due obligations, Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
China has all along stood for the complete prohibition and
thorough destruction of nuclear weapons. It pursues a policy of
not advocating, encouraging or engaging in the proliferation of
nuclear weapons, nor helping other countries to develop nuclear
weapons, the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Japan, Canada, the 13 non-nuclear-weapon countries in the
European Union, and the three nuclear powers of the United
States, Britain and France have signed the additional protocol
with the IAEA.
</P>
<P>
The director-general expressed gratitude to China's consistent
support for his agency, saying the IAEA will further strengthen
its cooperation with China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
