<HEADLINE> Ecuador Closes 1998 with 44-Percent Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador ended 1998 with an
annual inflation rate of 44 percent, the highest in Latin
America, said an official source here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Ecuador achieved 1.4 percent economic growth,
registered a 1.4-billion-U.S.-dollar budget deficit and a
negative trade balance of about one billion dollars with sucre,
the national currency, devalued by 54 percent.
</P>
<P>
Government officials attributed the economic slump to a number
of factors including the "El Nino" phenomenon and the drop in oil
prices.
</P>
<P>
"El Nino" caused a loss of more than 1.6 billion dollars to
Ecuador and produced a negative impact on the economic
development.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, Ecuador's gross domestic product grew 1.4 percent
compared with 3.4 percent in 1997, with the export of crude oil
and bananas plummeting to 300 million and 600 million dollars
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The small demand for bananas in the international market,
caused by the world financial turmoil, and the fall of crude oil
price led to a drop in the two products' exports, which are the
main pillars of Ecuador's economy.
</P>
<P>
President Jamil Mahuad announced that the sucre was devalued
and subsidies for electricity and fuel were eliminated on
September 14 last year, following a ratification of a tax on capit
al circulation two years earlier.
</P>
<P>
The government's goals for 1999 are to reduce the budget
deficit of 1.4 billion dollars and resume economic development.
It also expects to reduce inflation rate to between 24 percent
and 29 percent and to increase the gross domestic product to 2.5
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
