<HEADLINE> Austrian Government Hails Birth of Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, December 31 (Xinhua) -- After European Union (EU)
finance ministers approved the rates for the conversion of 11
currencies into the euro, Austrian government officials Thursday
hailed the birth of the euro as a "quantum leap" forward for
European integration.
</P>
<P>
The euro will become legal tender in 11 countries of the
European Union on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"The euro will become a powerful arm to strengthen the world
economy," Chancellor Viktor Klima said, adding that the European
single currency will become a central force for Europe's common
growth and employment plans through the coordination of economic
policies.
</P>
<P>
He said the approval of the euro conversion rates "ushers in a
new era for European politics."
</P>
<P>
Deputy Chancellor and Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schuessel said
the single currency will further Europe's economic growth,
employment and stability.
</P>
<P>
Schuessel said the birth of the euro will be "a quantum leap
forward for European integration".
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Rudolf Edlinger said the single currency is
"a successful result of 40 years of unremitting efforts toward
European integration."
</P>
<P>
The time of euro initiation is "very ideal," Edlinger said,
adding that the EU countries, the euro-zone countries in
particular, are now witnessing good economic growth, low
inflation and interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Klaus Liescher, president of the State Bank of Austria, said,
"Today is a great day for Europe."
</P>
<P>
Guenter Stumnvoll, secretary general of the Federal Chamber of
Commerce, said the birth of the euro is a most important step
toward integration.
</P>
<P>
The countries participating in the euro are Austria, Belgium,
Germany, Finland, France, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the
Netherlands, Portugal and Spain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
