<HEADLINE> FM Spokesman Resents over U.S. Satellite Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- China expressed its strong
resent over the U.S. House of Representatives' charges on U.S.
satellite technology deals with China, a Foreign Ministry
spokesman has said.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Bangzao noted that these charges do not tally with the
truth and are a "sheer fabrication".
</P>
<P>
A report by a special House committee investigating
technological transfer deals with China claimed technological
deals with China, including use of Chinese rockets to launch
U.S. satellites, have harmed the U.S. national security.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the report is an ill distortion of China's peaceful
use of space technology, thus deliberately undermining the
China-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that China hopes the U.S. government, viewing from
the point of the shared interests of bilateral long-term
cooperation, strictly observe the agreements signed between the
two governments on the commercial launching service and properly
handle the Chinese rockets' launching of U.S. satellites, in an
effort to safeguard the normal international commercial activities.
</P>
<P>
He noted that a spokesman for the China Aerospace Corporation
has refuted the charges and insisted the service, a normal
commercial activity, has always been in line with common
international practice, upheld the principle of fairness and
transparency and conformed to the three agreements between the
two governments.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the Chinese launching of U.S. satellites is in the
interests of the two nations.
</P>
<P>
"It is unnecessary, also impossible, for China to obtain
satellite, rocket and missile technology through commercial
launching service," Zhu added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
