<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Non-Oil/Gas Exports Expected to Grow 4-5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's non-oil/gas exports
are expected to grow by 4 to 5 percent next year with a total
value of 44 to 45 billion U.S. dollars, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"By taking into account various problems and economic
conditions which are still full of uncertainties, the growth of
the non-oil/gas exports is projected at 4 to 5 percent by 1999,"
Industry and Trade Minister Rahardi Ramelan said Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
The projection of non-oil/gas exports was also based on the
world economy which was expected to improve by 1999 due to several
factors, such as the improved economy of European Union countries
following the introduction of Euro single currency, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the improvement in the United States' economy as a
result of a seven-year economic expansion program and the
strengthening of the crisis-hit Asian countries' currencies would
also contribute to the attainment of the non-oil/gas export
growth, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The cut in banking interests in some crisis-hit countries and
the improved economies in Latin American countries would boost
Indonesia's non-oil/gas exports, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister believed that if the Japanese economy improved and
China did not devaluate its currency, then the economies of Asian
nations, including Indonesia, would become increasingly sound.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's non-oil/gas exports from 1993 to 1997 grew by an
average of 11.59 percent annually, while from 1994 to 1998 the
annual growth averaged 9.02 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said the country's total exports in the first 10
months of 1998 dropped by 6.88 percent from a corresponding period
last year.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's exports in the first 10 months of 1998 reached
41.03 billion U.S. dollars, including oil/gas exports worth 5.65
billion dollars and non-oil/gas exports valued at 34.46 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The oil/gas exports dropped by 32.13 percent while the
non-oil/gas exports increased by 0.22 percent compared to the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, Indonesia's total imports in
January-October also dropped by 36 percent to 22.56 billion U.S.
dollars. The oil/gas imports and non-oil/gas imports dropped by
30.74 percent and 36.54 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Rahardi said that in 1999 the government would be proactive in
struggling for national interests amid the increasingly fierce
competition on the global market.
</P>
<P>
"In 1999 Indonesia will always play a constructive role in
creating free, open and fair multilateral trade system," he said.
</P>
<P>
One of the global issues which should receive attention was
that all members of the World Trade Organization (WTO) should
fully and faithfully implement agreements reached at the Uruguay
Round trade dialogue, he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
