<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Lower House Passes 1999 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's Chamber of
Deputies (lower house) Thursday approved a
103-billion-U.S.-dollar federation budget for 1999.
</P>
<P>
The budget was passed with 340 votes from the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) and the National Action
Party (PAN).
</P>
<P>
The main opposition political forces, which include the
Democratic Revolution Party (PRD), the Labor Party (PT) and the
Mexican Ecologist Green Party (PVEM), rejected the budget bill.
</P>
<P>
The approved budget is based on an estimated income from oil,
which is expected to be around 9.25 dollars per barrel in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The new budget estimates that the inflation rate for next year
will be 13 percent, the economic growth rate will be 3 percent
and the average interest rate will be 21.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The public deficit proposed by the approved budget foresees a
level of 25 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP), less
than that of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Public Education Ministry was given first priority in the
budget with 7.06 billion dollars, which seems to demonstrate that
the Ernesto Zedillo government attaches importance to education.
</P>
<P>
The defense spending on the Mexican armed forces will be 2.32
billion dollars, including 1.65 billion dollars for the National
Defense Ministry and 660 million for the Navy Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The budget for other ministries, such as agriculture,
livestock and rural development is 2.11 billion dollars, and the
Finance and Public Credit Ministry is 1.77 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry is the fifth largest with budget
expenditures of 1.72 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
