<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Refutes U.S. Congressional Charges on Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The charges by a United States
congressional committee on U.S. satellite technology deals with
China do not tally with the truth and are a sheer fabrication, a
spokesman for the China Aerospace Corporation (CASC) said.
</P>
<P>
The charges included in a report by a special House committee
investigating military and commercial deals with China have
"greatly damaged the good image and international reputation of
the Long March rocket as well as the producer and launcher of the
rocket", the spokesman said in an interview with Xinhua last night.
</P>
<P>
China's commercial launching service is an important outcome of
the reform and opening-up policy, which aims at making peaceful
use of space technology, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of both China and the United States have made
positive efforts to promote trade in commercial launching service
between the two countries for more than a decade, the spokesman
said, noting that the two governments have signed three agreements
on the issue, which shows a strong sense of responsibility on
launching U.S.-made satellites by Long March rockets.
</P>
<P>
"China's commercial launching service has always been in line
with common international practice, upheld the principle of
fairness and transparency and conformed to the three agreements
between the governments of China and the United States," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that while the technological security of U.S.-made
satellites is fully guaranteed, even if a breakdown occurs, the
investigation, analysis and decision on further measures are all
done independently by Chinese experts.
</P>
<P>
"The past experiences indicate that those measures are fully
effective and it is unnecessary, also impossible, for us to obtain
rocket and missile technology from U.S. satellite companies," the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He said that U.S. media and some House representatives have
misled the public by mixing up the conceptions of carrier rockets
and missiles, and blurred up the differences between normal
technological coordination and leakage of technology.
</P>
<P>
"Some people even take a biased stand on normal international
trade to serve certain political interests," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Those descriptions and behavior, while hurting the Chinese
aerospace industry, will do more harm to U.S. satellite producers
and users," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that U.S. congressmen of insight will take a prudent
approach in handling the issue and make sensible judgement in line
with the truth," the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
