<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Communist Party Diplomacy Makes Headway (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, January 1 (Xinhua) -- Twenty years ago, the Chinese
Communist Party (CPC), which had the largest number of party
members anywhere in the world, maintained a few links with foreign
communist parties. Then by telling friends from enemies just
according to ideologies, the CPC's foreign relations were in an
impasse.
</P>
<P>
Today, matters are much changed and the CPC, which leads one
fifth of the world's population, has set up contacts and exchanges
with over 340 political parties of all types, in nearly 140
countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Dai Bingguo, head of the International Department of the CPC
Central Committee in charge of the party's diplomatic work, told
Xinhua in an exclusive interview that along with China's rising
international status, the Party's diplomatic skills have become a
part of inter-state relations in order to better serve the
country's overall foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
In the last year, the 20th anniversary of the launch of China's
reform and opening-up policy, two notable achievements in the
CPC's external relations were recorded: the relationship between
the two communist parties of China and Japan was resumed after a
32-year suspension, and the president of the International
Socialist Party visited China for the first time in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that a new pattern in the CPC's
diplomatic work has emerged, in which it keeps in touch with
various party forces, including ruling parties, power-sharing
parties, opposition parties, and even political parties in
countries which have no diplomatic ties with China.
</P>
<P>
The CPC's brand-new foreign relations policy, which ignores
ideological differences, has shown unprecedented vigor and
vitality, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990101.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
