<DOCNO> XIE19990101.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Communist Party Diplomacy Makes Headway (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In another development, the CPC has maintained frequent and
in-depth exchanges with major parties in almost all neighboring
countries, contributing to a good-neighborly, peaceful and stable
environment for China's modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
While strengthening and developing exchanges and cooperation
with over 160 parties in developing countries, the CPC also
carried on candid dialogues with parties in developed countries in
an effort to bring up the positive elements in bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats say that, with friends in both ruling parties and
non-ruling parties, the CPC has helped China maintain sustainable
and stable ties with multi-party countries when power reshuffles
occur. Around 10 presidents in Latin America, for example, had
visited China at the invitation of the CPC before they assumed
their presidency.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 20 years, the CPC has forged ties with over 40
major parties in a total of 17 countries yet to establish ties
with China, which helps expedite both countries on their way to
forging diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
When it comes to such major issues as Taiwan, Tibet and human
rights, the CPC always tries to promote common understandings and
reduce divergencies through party-channel dialogues, and in
return, has won understandings and support from many parties and
international figures in favor of China's stance.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the CPC has included economic exchanges in its
foreign relations framework in addition to political-themed talks,
and has made active efforts to promote economic and trade ties
between China and foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Casting his eyes upon the future of CPC foreign relations at
the turn of the century, Dai noted that the CPC will continue to
make every effort to explore more favorable and peaceful
international conditions for the ongoing reform and opening-up and
modernization drive right now in full swing in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
