<DOCNO> XIE19990101.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's 1998 Per Capita GDP Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, January 1 (Xinhua) -- The prolonged economic crisis
has made both Indonesia's per capita Gross Domestic Product (GDP)
and per capita Gross National Product (GNP) in 1998 lower than
those in 1997, the Central Bureau of Statistics said.
</P>
<P>
Based on the 1993 constant prices (one dollar equaled 2,123
rupiah), Indonesia's per capita GDP in 1998 dropped from 2.2
million rupiah in 1997 to 1.8 million, while the country's per
capita GNP fell from 2.1 million rupiah to 1.8 million rupiah,
Antara News Agency Friday quoted chief of the bureau Sugito Suwito
as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, if measured on the basis of the prevailing prices, the
country's per capita GDP increased to 4.9 million rupiah (one U.S.
dollar equals 8,000 rupiah now), compared with the previous year's
3.1 million rupiah, Sugito said.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, the per capita GNP in 1998 was recorded at 4.6
million rupiah, up from the 3 million rupiah in 1997, he added.
</P>
<P>
The economic crisis caused changes in the 1998 GDP structure.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture sector enhanced its role in the GDP for the
first time in 30 years, increasing from 16.01 percent in 1997 to
18.82 percent. The mining sector in 1998 also increased its role
from 8.71 percent to 12.86 percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
The industry sector also increased its share from 25.54 percent
to 26.23 percent, as the oil/gas industry could continue
production, Sugito said.
</P>
<P>
However, the role of the property and trade sectors in the GDP
declined from 7.38 percent and 16.59 percent to 5.44 percent and
14.9 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
The role of the transportation and service sectors in the GDP
also dropped from 6.75 percent and 8.36 percent to 5.42 percent
and 6.91 percent respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990101.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Ends 1998 With 29.9 Percent Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Venezuela ends 1998 with a
29.9 percent inflation, among the highest in Latin America, the
Central Bank of Venezuela announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, this year's inflation index variation has been the
least for the country since 1986, and has showed a deceleration
compared to 1997 when it registered a 37.6 percent rate.
</P>
<P>
The deceleration is linked to an important drop in the
domestic demand, produced by the contraction of public spending
and increases in the interest rates, Antonio Casas Gonzalez,
Central Bank president, said in his year-end message.
</P>
<P>
The government of Rafael Caldera had to cut its spending by
3.2 billion U.S. dollars in 1998, because of a 7 billion dollar
shortfall in oil income caused by the international crude prices
drop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
