<HEADLINE> Dow Down at Yearend, Up 16 Percent for Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 31 (Xinhua) -- Blue-chip stocks closed lower
on Wall Street Thursday, but technology shares surged to a record
high in the last session of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 93.21 to 9,181.43,
sitting 16.1 percent above the year's starting point, but 192
points below the record high of 9,374.27 reached on December 23.
</P>
<P>
The technology-rich Nasdaq composite index ended the year at a
new high of 2,192.69, up 25.74 points from Wednesday, representing
a 39.6 percent growth for the year.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 2.70 to 1,229.23, up 26.7
percent for the year.
</P>
<P>
Advancers led decliners 3-1 with more active trading than two
previous sessions. A total of 726 million shares changed hands on
the New York Stock Exchange whose composite index rose 1.54 to
595.81.
</P>
<P>
The American Stock Exchange composite index rose 16.92 to
688.99 and the Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose a
staggering 10.05 to 421.96.
</P>
<P>
Analysts see Wall Street's 1998 performance as strong as it has
retained the double digit growth in major market indicators since
1995, thanks to a stable economy expected to grow around 3.5
percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Some say that the stock market may face a correction some time
next year, as the economy is expected to see an expansion of
slower pace amid a not so strong consumer spending and bleak U.S.
exports to crisis-hit countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
