<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian President Firmly Believes in Success of Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The year 1998 has been
tormented and difficult and it will remain enshrined in the books
of the future as a threshold in the history of this long and
winding road of the reform, Romanian President Emil Constantinescu
said Thursday night in his New Year message.
</P>
<P>
The president said that the year "began with a governmental
crisis and ended with a relaunching of radical, firm reform
measures we need so desperately in order to privatize large
enterprises and banks, curtail economic losses, tame the inflation
and regain the lost ground on foreign capital markets."
</P>
<P>
Should these processes go on as fast as they have in the past
two months, Romanians may start picking up the fruits of all the
sacrifices they have committed in the last 10 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
On a regional plan Romania has won unanimous appreciation as a
pillar of stability and balance thanks to its ties with its
friends in the neighborhood, he said. He added that Romania has
also earned a place along the trans-continental routes likely to
dominate the global society of the third millennium. "All these
have definitely fetched us security and high esteem from around
the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
In reference to the efforts and sacrifices the Romanian people
should enact in the near future, the president said
metaphorically, "There is a bridge that spans a troubled water
ahead of us and we must step across it. The countries that have
done it already can now enjoy more wealth and more security. The
indecisive are suffering from lack of capital, overdue wages and
pensions, violent actions carried out by mafia-like structures."
</P>
<P>
"As for ourselves," he stressed, "we are ready to cross the
bridge."
</P>
<P>
To do it right and in due time, he said, "we need three things:
to bear the conviction that we will be better off once across the
other bank, to act fearlessly, and to help one another as we all
shall have to cross this river." 
</P>
</TEXT>
