<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Urges Angola's Cooperation Over Air Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 31 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council Thursday voted 15-0 to adopt a resolution, demanding that
the conflicting parties in Angola immediate allow rescue
operations of a downed U.N. plane with 14 aboard over territory
where fierce fighting is raging on.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted at an urgent meeting on Angola, the
15-nation council deplored "the incomprehensible lack of
cooperation clarifying the circumstances of this tragedy" in the
central highland province of Huambo, Angola.
</P>
<P>
The council convened the urgent session during the holiday
break at the request of the Russian Mission to the United Nations,
about five days after the U.N.-chartered C-130 cargo plane crashed
Saturday with 10 passengers and four crew members aboard,
including U.N. peacekeepers in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The plane flew over embattled territory after taking off from
Huambo, Angola's second largest city.
</P>
<P>
The resolution demanded Jonas Savimbi, head of the rebel
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA),
respond immediately to appeals from the United Nations that would
"guarantee the security and access necessary for" a resue mission.
</P>
<P>
It also called on the Angolan Government to cooperate "as
appropriate in fulfillment of its expressed commitment to do so."
</P>
<P>
The Angolan Government, which U.N. officials said also ignored
numerous U.N. appeals, reportedly said it would cooperate with the
United Nations over the plane crash just minutes before the
council's urgent meeting, but it gave no details on how this would
be done.
</P>
<P>
Also Thursday, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan issued a
statement, saying that he has requested Benon Sevan,
under-secretary-general and United Nations security coordinator,
"depart for Angola as soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
The statement said, "As part of his urgent efforts to assure
the swiftest possible implementation of a search and rescue
mission to the crash site of the United Nations plane in Angola,
the secretary-general has requested that Mr. Benon Sevan,
under-secretary-general and United Nations security coordinator,
depart for Angola as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
"In addition to helping facilitate a mission to the crash site,
as well as an investigation into the cause of crash, the United
Nations security coordinator will assess the growing threat to
United Nations personnel throughout Angola," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general expects the responsible leaders in
Angola to provide all possible assistance to the United Nations
security coordinator in his mission," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has a 1,000 peacekeepers in Angola to
supervise crumbling 1994 peace accords that were to have ended
more than two decades of civil war in the former Portuguese colony
in southwest Africa.
</P>
<P>
The 185-member world body has asked UNITA and the Angolan
Government for a cease-fire so that rescue teams could operate
safely. However, artillery barrages continued with at least six
civilians killed and 20 others injured in Huambo Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
